  "prompt": "What could cause your period to be 14 days late other than pregnancy?",
  "response": "A variety of factors can contribute to a delayed menstrual cycle beyond pregnancy. Some common causes include:\n\n1. **Stress:** High levels of stress can affect the hormones responsible for regulating the menstrual cycle, leading to delayed periods.\n2. **Weight Changes:** Significant weight gain or loss can disrupt hormonal balance, affecting the timing of your period.\n3. **Exercise:** Excessive physical activity, particularly in athletes, can lead to irregular periods due to hormonal changes.\n4. **Medical Conditions:** Conditions such as polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), thyroid disorders, or ovarian cysts can interfere with the menstrual cycle.\n5. **Medications:** Certain medications, including hormonal contraceptives and treatments for other conditions, can affect menstrual regularity.\n6. **Illness:** Acute or chronic illnesses can temporarily disrupt your menstrual cycle.\n7. **Perimenopause:** For individuals nearing menopause, hormonal changes can lead to irregular periods.\n8. **Travel:** Changes in routine, time zones, or environment can stress your body and impact your cycle.\n9. **Lifestyle Factors:** Poor diet, insufficient sleep, or other lifestyle factors can also influence menstrual timing.\n\nIf your period is significantly late and you are concerned, it is recommended to consult a healthcare professional for a thorough evaluation.",
